1. n8n: webhook workflow
New workflow → add Webhook (trigger).
HTTP Method: POST.
Path: e.g. wazuh-alerts (production URL will look like .../webhook/wazuh-alerts or similar depending on n8n version).
Response: “Respond immediately” or a simple 200 JSON so Wazuh doesn’t wait long (integrator has timeouts).
Authentication (strongly recommended):
In Webhook node: Header Auth or Query Auth with a secret only Wazuh will send.
Or use n8n’s webhook Authentication options if your version exposes them.
Save and Activate the workflow.
Copy the Production webhook URL.
Add nodes after the webhook: Set / Code to normalize payload, then your actions (Slack, email, HTTP, etc.). Wazuh sends JSON when alert_format is json—inspect one execution to see the exact shape.

2. Connectivity: what to put in hook_url
The Wazuh manager container must reach n8n. localhost inside the manager is wrong (that’s the manager itself).

Pick one:

Setup	Example hook_url idea
Shared Docker network (both stacks attached to the same external network, e.g. Hostinger Traefik shared network)	http://<n8n_service_name>:5678/webhook/... (internal port 5678, not 32768)
Via host published port (manager → host IP → n8n)	http://<VPS_LAN_or_bridge_IP>:32768/webhook/... using the host port you showed (32768)
Public HTTPS (n8n behind Traefik with a hostname)	https://n8n.yourdomain.com/webhook/...
Test from inside the manager container (Hostinger terminal / docker exec):

curl -sS -o /dev/null -w "%{http_code}" -X POST "YOUR_WEBHOOK_URL" -H "Content-Type: application/json" -d "{}"
You want 200 (or whatever your webhook returns). Fix DNS/network until this works before editing Wazuh.

3. Wazuh manager: custom integration
Edit the manager config (on the VPS: typically ossec.conf or a fragment under etc/ossec.conf.d/ depending on image). Add something like:

<integration>
  <name>custom-n8n</name>
  <hook_url>https://YOUR_N8N_HOST/webhook/SECRET_PATH</hook_url>
  <alert_format>json</alert_format>
  <level>7</level>
</integration>
Adjust:

hook_url: full production webhook URL (include any secret header only if Wazuh supports it—see note below).
level: minimum rule level to forward (e.g. 7 or 10); omit to send more alerts (noisy).
Optional filters from the docs: rule_id, group, event_location, etc.
Official reference: integration (ossec.conf).

Headers: If n8n requires Authorization or X-My-Secret, check whether your Wazuh version’s custom integration supports extra headers in options or if you need a tiny proxy; many setups use a long random path as the secret instead.

Restart the Wazuh manager after saving (Docker: restart the manager container / stack).

4. Verify
n8n → Executions: confirm incoming runs when alerts fire.
Wazuh manager logs if silent: look for integratord / integration errors.
Temporarily lower <level> or widen filters if you get nothing (or generate a test alert).
5. Order of operations
Webhook workflow active in n8n.
curl from manager container to webhook OK.
<integration> on manager + restart.
Tune level / rule_id / group so n8n isn’t flooded.
If you paste how n8n and Wazuh compose projects join networks (or your n8n service name + whether they share an external network), we can narrow hook_url to a single line (internal vs host:32768 vs public URL).